The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` is the modern web component replacement for the legacy `Autocomplete` widget. You append it to the DOM directly and listen for the `gmp-placeselect` event, which fires when a user selects a suggestion. After selection, you call `fetchFields()` on the returned `Place` object to retrieve the specific data you need [Source 1, Source 2].

Here's a complete working example:

```javascript
async function initAutocomplete() {
  // Load the places library
  await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

  // Create the PlaceAutocompleteElement
  const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" }, // Restrict to US results
  });

  // Append it to your container element
  document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

  // Listen for a place selection
  placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
    const place = event.place;

    // Fetch only the fields you need (you're only billed for what you request)
    await place.fetchFields({
      fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
    });

    console.log("Name:", place.displayName);
    console.log("Address:", place.formattedAddress);
    console.log("Lat/Lng:", place.location.lat(), place.location.lng());

    // Example: pan the map to the selected place
    if (place.location) {
      map.setCenter(place.location);
      map.setZoom(15);
    }
  });
}
```

A few things worth noting:

- **Field masking matters for cost** — only request the fields you actually need in `fetchFields()`. Each field group is billed separately [Source 2].
- **`gmp-placeselect` vs `place_changed`** — the new element uses `gmp-placeselect`, not the legacy `place_changed` event used by the old `Autocomplete` class.
- **No `getPlace()` call needed** — unlike the legacy widget, the selected `Place` object comes directly from `event.place`. You still need to call `fetchFields()` to hydrate the data you want.
- The element renders its own styled input, so you don't need to wire it up to a separate `<input>` tag like the legacy `Autocomplete` required.

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)

Based on the retrieved documentation, here are the key Google Maps Platform features currently deprecated and being replaced:

---

## 1. `google.maps.Marker` → `AdvancedMarkerElement`

The legacy `Marker` class is deprecated. The replacement `AdvancedMarkerElement` offers better performance, accessibility, custom HTML content support, and improved collision handling [Source 1].

**Requirements for the new element:**
- A `mapId` must be provided in the Map constructor
- The `marker` library must be explicitly imported
- Custom icons use the `content` HTML property instead of the `icon` property

```javascript
// OLD (deprecated)
const marker = new google.maps.Marker({
  position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
  map,
  title: "NYC",
  icon: "custom-icon.png",
});

// NEW (recommended)
const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("marker");
const marker = new AdvancedMarkerElement({
  position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
  map,
  title: "NYC",
});
```

---

## 2. Legacy Places API (`PlacesService`) → Places API (New)

The callback-based `PlacesService` is being replaced by the promise-based `Place` class [Source 1]. Key changes include:

| Legacy | New |
|--------|-----|
| `PlacesService.getDetails()` | `Place.fetchFields()` |
| `PlacesService.findPlaceFromQuery()` | `Place.searchByText()` |
| `PlacesService.nearbySearch()` | `Place.searchNearby()` |
| `PlacesService.textSearch()` | `Place.searchByText()` |

The new API also **requires field masking**, meaning you only pay for the fields you explicitly request — a significant cost optimization [Source 3].

```javascript
// OLD (legacy)
const service = new google.maps.places.PlacesService(map);
service.getDetails(
  { placeId: "ChIJ...", fields: ["name", "geometry"] },
  (place, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.places.PlacesServiceStatus.OK) {
      console.log(place.name);
    }
  }
);

// NEW (recommended)
const { Place } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
const place = new Place({ id: "ChIJ..." });
await place.fetchFields({ fields: ["displayName", "location"] });
console.log(place.displayName);
```

---

## 3. Inline Map Styles (`styles` array) → Cloud-Based Styling

Passing a `styles` array directly to the `Map` constructor is deprecated. The replacement is Cloud-based map styling via a **Map ID** configured in the Google Cloud Console [Source 1].

```javascript
// OLD (deprecated)
const map = new google.maps.Map(element, {
  styles: [
    { featureType: "water", stylers: [{ color: "#004358" }] },
  ],
});

// NEW (recommended)
const map = new google.maps.Map(element, {
  mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID", // Style configured in Cloud Console
});
```

**Benefits of Cloud-based styling:** update styles without code changes, A/B test styles, consistent styling across web/Android/iOS, and better performance since styles are applied server-side [Source 2].

---

## General Recommendations

To stay ahead of deprecations [Source 2]:
- Monitor your browser console for deprecation warnings
- Use `v: "weekly"` or `v: "beta"` to preview upcoming changes
- Review the migration guides quarterly

---

**Sources:**
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Maps JavaScript API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview)

Loading the Maps JavaScript API in a React app requires some care to avoid common pitfalls like re-initialization on re-renders and SSR issues (if you're using Next.js). Here's the recommended approach:

## Option 1: `@googlemaps/js-api-loader` (Recommended)

This is the cleanest approach for React. Install the package and use it inside a `useEffect` with a `useRef` to prevent re-initialization:

```javascript
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import { Loader } from "@googlemaps/js-api-loader";

export default function MapComponent() {
  const mapRef = useRef(null);
  const mapInstanceRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (mapRef.current && !mapInstanceRef.current) {
      const loader = new Loader({
        apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
        version: "weekly",
      });

      loader.importLibrary("maps").then(async ({ Map }) => {
        const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await loader.importLibrary("marker");

        mapInstanceRef.current = new Map(mapRef.current, {
          center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
          zoom: 12,
          mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID", // Required for AdvancedMarkerElement
        });

        // Example: Add a marker
        new AdvancedMarkerElement({
          map: mapInstanceRef.current,
          position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
          title: "New York City",
        });
      });
    }

    // Cleanup event listeners on unmount
    return () => {
      if (mapInstanceRef.current) {
        google.maps.event.clearInstanceListeners(mapInstanceRef.current);
      }
    };
  }, []);

  return <div ref={mapRef} style={{ width: "100%", height: "400px" }} />;
}
```

## Option 2: Dynamic Script Tag (without npm package)

If you'd prefer not to use the npm package, you can use the inline bootstrap snippet directly via a `useEffect`. The key pattern is the same — initialize once, guard with `useRef`:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  async function initMap() {
    const { Map } = await google.maps.importLibrary("maps");
    if (mapRef.current && !mapInstanceRef.current) {
      mapInstanceRef.current = new Map(mapRef.current, {
        center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
        zoom: 12,
      });
    }
  }
  initMap();
}, []);
```

## If You're Using Next.js

The Maps API requires `window`, which doesn't exist during server-side rendering. Wrap your map component in a dynamic import with `ssr: false`:

```javascript
// pages/index.js or app/page.js
import dynamic from "next/dynamic";

const MapComponent = dynamic(() => import("../components/MapComponent"), {
  ssr: false,
  loading: () => <div>Loading map...</div>,
});

export default function Page() {
  return <MapComponent />;
}
```

## Key Patterns to Follow

- **Use `useRef` + `useEffect`** to initialize the map once and avoid re-creating it on every render [Source 2].
- **Guard with `!mapInstanceRef.current`** so the map isn't re-initialized if the component re-renders.
- **Clean up event listeners** in the `useEffect` return function to prevent memory leaks [Source 2].
- **Use `AdvancedMarkerElement`** instead of the deprecated `google.maps.Marker` [Source 1].
- **`mapId` is required** if you plan to use `AdvancedMarkerElement` [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Maps JavaScript API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview)
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)

## Directions API vs. Routes API

These are related but distinct — the Routes API is the modern server-side replacement for the legacy Directions API, while the JavaScript API's `DirectionsService` remains the recommended approach for client-side routing.

Here's a breakdown of the key differences [Source 5]:

| Feature | Legacy Directions API | Routes API (New) |
|---|---|---|
| **Status** | Still works, not recommended | Recommended for server-side routing |
| **Field masking** | Not supported | Required (pay only for what you use) |
| **Traffic modeling** | Basic | Improved |
| **Polyline quality** | Standard | Multiple options |
| **Toll information** | No | Yes |
| **Two-wheeler routing** | No | Yes |

### Server-Side: Routes API (REST)

For backend or direct REST usage, the Routes API is the clear choice. The field mask header is critical — it controls both the response payload and your billing [Source 1]:

```javascript
// POST https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes
// Headers:
//   X-Goog-Api-Key: YOUR_API_KEY
//   X-Goog-FieldMask: routes.duration,routes.distanceMeters,routes.polyline.encodedPolyline

const response = await fetch("https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "X-Goog-Api-Key": "YOUR_API_KEY",
    "X-Goog-FieldMask": "routes.duration,routes.distanceMeters,routes.polyline.encodedPolyline"
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    origin: {
      location: { latLng: { latitude: 40.7128, longitude: -74.0060 } }
    },
    destination: {
      location: { latLng: { latitude: 34.0522, longitude: -118.2437 } }
    },
    travelMode: "DRIVE",
    routingPreference: "TRAFFIC_AWARE"
  })
});
```

### Client-Side: DirectionsService (still recommended)

For displaying routes in a map UI, `DirectionsService` and `DirectionsRenderer` in the Maps JavaScript API remain the recommended approach [Source 5]:

```javascript
const directionsService = new google.maps.DirectionsService();
const directionsRenderer = new google.maps.DirectionsRenderer();

directionsRenderer.setMap(map);

directionsService.route(
  {
    origin: "New York, NY",
    destination: "Boston, MA",
    travelMode: google.maps.TravelMode.DRIVING,
  },
  (result, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.DirectionsStatus.OK) {
      directionsRenderer.setDirections(result);
    } else {
      console.error("Directions request failed:", status);
    }
  }
);
```

### Pricing Reminder

The Routes API uses tiered pricing based on the `routingPreference` you select [Source 4]:

- `TRAFFIC_UNAWARE` → **$5.00** / 1,000 requests (Basic)
- `TRAFFIC_AWARE` → **$10.00** / 1,000 requests (Advanced)
- `TRAFFIC_AWARE_OPTIMAL` → **$15.00** / 1,000 requests (Preferred)

**Bottom line**: Use `DirectionsService` for client-side map rendering, and the Routes API REST endpoint for server-side route computation where you need features like toll data, two-wheeler routing, or precise field masking.

**Sources:**
- [Routes API and Directions](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/routes/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

The `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` error means you've exceeded either your queries-per-second (QPS) or daily quota limit for a given API. This can happen when you're making too many requests in a short time window or have hit your configured daily ceiling.

There are a few ways to resolve it:

1. **Implement exponential backoff** — retry failed requests with increasing delays
2. **Batch requests** where the API supports it
3. **Check and increase your quota** in Cloud Console > APIs & Services > Quotas
4. **Request a quota increase** from Google if your legitimate usage requires it

Here's a retry helper with exponential backoff for geocoding requests:

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  const geocoder = new google.maps.Geocoder();

  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Wait 1s, then 2s, then 4s before retrying
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000));
        continue;
      }
      throw error; // Re-throw if out of retries or different error
    }
  }
}
```

You can also proactively prevent hitting quota limits by setting a daily request cap in the Cloud Console (APIs & Services > Google Maps Platform > Quotas & System Limits), so unexpected traffic spikes don't generate surprise overages [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

You should use the new **PlaceAutocompleteElement** (web component) or the **`Place` class** from the Places API (New). The legacy `PlacesService` and callback-based `AutocompleteService` are being replaced, and the new API offers significant advantages: native Promise support, required field masking (so you only pay for what you request), better TypeScript support, and simpler session token handling [Source 2].

There are two modern options depending on your use case:

**Option 1: `PlaceAutocompleteElement`** — The recommended drop-in UI widget. It handles the input field, suggestions dropdown, and session tokens automatically [Source 1]:

```javascript
const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
  componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
});

// Append it to your page
document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

// Listen for a place selection
placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
  const place = event.place;
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
  });
  console.log(place.displayName, place.formattedAddress);
});
```

**Option 2: Legacy `Autocomplete` widget** — Still functional, but `PlaceAutocompleteElement` is the forward-looking choice [Source 2]:

```javascript
const { Autocomplete } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const autocomplete = new Autocomplete(
  document.getElementById("search-input"),
  {
    types: ["geocode", "establishment"],
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
    fields: ["place_id", "geometry", "formatted_address", "name"],
  }
);

autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", () => {
  const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
  if (!place.geometry) {
    console.error("No geometry returned for this place.");
    return;
  }
  map.setCenter(place.geometry.location);
  map.setZoom(15);
});
```

**On billing**: Make sure you're using session tokens if you go with a programmatic approach (i.e., not `PlaceAutocompleteElement`). Without them, every keystroke is billed as a separate Autocomplete request at $2.83/1,000. With session tokens, the entire session plus the final Place Details call is billed as one [Source 3 / Source 5].

```javascript
// Manual session token usage with AutocompleteService
const sessionToken = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteSessionToken();
const service = new google.maps.places.AutocompleteService();
service.getPlacePredictions({ input: "pizza", sessionToken }, (predictions) => {
  // handle predictions
});
// Token is consumed when you fetch place details
```

`PlaceAutocompleteElement` handles session tokens for you automatically, which is another reason to prefer it.

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)
